[2] Algeria (Naama province): canine, human exposure, RFI
Date: Tue 9 Feb 2016
Source: Echorouk [in Arabic, trans. Mod.AB, edited]
http://www.echoroukonline.com/ara/articles/272309.html


At the end of last week [week of 1 Feb 2016], 3 children aged between 5 and 10 years old were bitten by a dog coming from the western side of Ain Sefra city [province of Naama]. The dog bit the hand of a 5-year-old child while the latter was leaving school at Al-Hammar district then ran away towards Assalam Malih district and bit the 2nd child's head and shoulder, which required transporting him swiftly to Mohamed Boudiaf Hospital in Ain Sefra. The dog continued his roaming toward Toukount village and bit another child on his way without being caught by the authorities.

A new trend in which some teenagers wander along streets accompanied by dogs of all kinds is becoming widespread. They rarely respect the conditions stipulated by the Ministry of Health, including their submission to rabies vaccination and their muzzling, especially since these dogs move into educational institutions and neighborhoods away from security officers. This poses a danger to children playing in front of their homes.

[Byline: A Khalifi]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-MENA
<promed-mena@promedmail.org>

[Dog rabies is enzootic throughout Algeria.

An apparently rabid dog bit 3 young children occasioning very severe lesions on their head, hand, and shoulder. Hopefully, the roaming dog was caught and the laboratory confirmation of rabies (or otherwise) was performed.

No information is provided on the extent of the problem of stray dogs in Naama province or whether any rabies prevention and control measures are taken as routine.

It will be appreciated if further information is disclosed on the post-exposure treatment provided to the injured children and on the action taken to stop the propagation of the disease in the region. - Mod.AB

Maps of Algeria can be seen at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/images/africa/political-map-of-Algeria.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4015862,17217. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

