[3] Egypt (Asyut): canine, human exposure, RFI
Date: Sun 7 Feb 2016
Source: Ahram [in Arabic, trans. Mod.AB, edited]
http://bit.ly/1NYLVYT


A total of 10 people were bitten today [7 Feb 2016] by a dog in the city of Ghanayem in Asyut governorate, which led to their injury with scratches scattered throughout their body, and their transfer to the Central hospitals of Sodfa and El Ghanayem.

The Asyut Security Directorate received a notice from the security officer of El Ghanayem city stating that 10 people were injured and presented multiple scratches, due to their being bit by a rabid dog.

The patients were transferred to central hospitals in Sodfa and El Ghanayem and a report of the incident was prepared and submitted for prosecution.

[Byline: Islam Radwan]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-MENA
<promed-mena@promedmail.org>

[It seems that a rabies outbreak is evolving in the governorate of Asyut, at least near El Ghanayem city (see map at https://goo.gl/maps/iRLqbriPxgm) and a roaming dog attacked people and made 10 victims who were severely bitten.

No information is provided on the extent of the problem of stray dogs in the governorate and whether any rabies prevention and control measure is taken as a routine. Also, it is not clear that the laboratory diagnosis of rabies was performed on the biting dog.

It will be appreciated if further information is disclosed on the post-exposure treatment provided to the injured and on the action taken to stop the propagation of the disease in the region. - Mod.AB

Maps of Egypt can be seen at http://www.geoatlas.com/medias/maps/countries/egypt/eg3r92t/egypt_pol.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4015862,51823. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

