[4] Israel (Northern): equine, canine, human exposure
Date: Wed 10 Feb 2016
Source: Arutz Sheva 7, Israel National News [edited]
http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/Flash.aspx/351185#.Vr4RCMfnesQ


The Ministry of Health has received reports of a horse that has been diagnosed with rabies. The horse was used for herding cattle by [Ha-Gomme] Junction.

The herders have received treatment to prevent them from coming down with the disease.

The Ministry is asking anyone who has had contact, or whose animals have been in contact with infected animals to contact the health offices in Tsfat. The same applies to anyone whose animals wandered around the area during the past 2 weeks.

Earlier this morning [Wed 10 Feb 2016], a rabid dog was found wandering around in the same area.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-MENA
<promed-mena@promedmail.org>

The affected horse, used by the cattlemen of a grazing cattle herd, was unvaccinated in spite of the recommendation to vaccinate grazing livestock (cattle and horses) in northern Israel bordering Syria and Lebanon. A map showing the region defined as "rabies high risk" (as updated in July 2015) is available at http://www.vetserv.moag.gov.il/NR/rdonlyres/00AA0CC1-AF95-419A-A50B-F9797CC9CAE8/0/kalevet_2015.pdf (in Hebrew).

The horse case is the 7th rabies case in animals in Israel since the beginning of 2016; the other (lab confirmed) cases were dogs (3), cattle (2), and a jackal. During the same period last year (2015), 4 cases were reported, within the same region.

Case no 6, reported rabid on 9 Feb 2016 in Qiryat Shemona, near case no 7, has been the most worrying one from public health perspective, exposing several persons, including veterinary personnel, to potential infection. According to the information provided by the Head of Israel's Field veterinary Services, the 6-month-old Pit-bull male dog was castrated (as required by law in regard to dogs listed as dangerous breeds) and compulsorily vaccinated against rabies on 25 Jan 2016. The dog had been acquired by the owner at the age of approximately 3 months. According to the owner, and as confirmed by the attending veterinary practitioner, the dog could not be vaccinated at the officially prescribed age of 3 months due to observed parvovirus infection. On 3 Feb 2016, the dog was brought to a veterinary clinic in view of "general fatigue" and was released the same day without specific findings. The next day the dog was brought back to the clinic suffering from diarrhea and vomiting. Abdominal x-raying next day disclosed foreign body which required immediate surgery during which a plastic cylinder was withdrawn. The dog seemed to be recovering but 2 days started to show neural signs, hypersensitivity, and aggressive behavior. The municipality veterinary officer was invited to the clinic for consultation, the dog was euthanized and the head submitted to the national rabies lab at Beit Dagan, where rabies was confirmed.

Rabies in puppies and young dogs is sometimes atypical. The case history above or its variations might be familiar to veterinary clinicians in rabies-stricken locations.

It may be assumed that both animals, dog and horse, have been exposed to an undetected rabid wild animal or a stray dog. Exposed people are being preventively treated by the public health authorities. - Mod.AS

Maps of Israel can be seen at http://www.eyeonisrael.com/Israel-touring-map.html and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4015862,51792. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
